Curriculum Vitae
Biography
 Publications




											Brief Bio
										
Dr. Robert Levy has been a Research Physical Scientist in the Climate and Radiation Laboratory (CRL) since 2013. Dr. Levy is focused on retrieving global aerosol properties from satellite observations, and using the retrieved products for quantifying the role of aerosols in climate and air quality.  He is responsible for maintaining the "dark-target" aerosol retrieval for MODIS, and applying it to VIIRS and other sensors to create a long-term global aerosol record. Dr. Levy’s research has ranged from applications of new algorithm development, monitoring surface air quality, aerosol/cloud interactions and aerosol trends.  His publication list and citation metrics can be found at ResearcherID.   

											Current Projects
										


													Fine tuning the MODIS dark target aerosol algorithm and products: comprehensive error analysis
												
												I am PI of this Terra/Aqua-Existing Data Products proposal.  The goal is to maintain and continue to improve the MODIS dark-target aerosol product. Primary tasks include developing a per-pixel retrieval uncertainty product, removing retrieval bias over urban areas, and moving towards greater data fusion with other satellite datasets and models. 




													Towards a consistent aerosol data record, created from MODIS, VIIRS and beyond
												
												I am PI of this project as part of the Suomi-NPP Science Team.  The goal is to apply the MODIS dark-target aerosol retrieval algorithm to VIIRS in order to create a continuous aerosol data record.  




													Studying aerosol in cloud fields using MAS data from SEAC4RS and previous field campaigns
												
												I am PI of this NASA-funded opportunity for Atmospheric Composition Campaign Data Analysis and Modeling.  We are porting the MODIS aerosol dark-target algorithm to use airborne eMAS observations.  Starting with the recent SEAC4RS experiment, we are looking to characterize aerosol in cloud fields at high resolution. 




													Study of aerosol properties in the vicinity of clouds using multiplatform and multisensor data fusion
												
												I am Co-I on this NASA-funded project aimed at enhancing The Science of Terra and Aqua. Our work will be characterize and correct for 3D radiative effects within the MODIS dark-target aerosol retrieval algorithm



											Education
										
										2007: Ph.D, Dept. of Atmospheric and Ocean Sciencies, University of Maryland-College Park, College Park, Maryland USA   1996: M.S., Dept. of Atmospheric Science, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, Colorado, USA   1994: B.A., Dept. of Mathematics, Oberlin College, Oberlin, Ohio USA  

											Professional Service
										
										2011-present: Member of MODIS Science Team  2012-present: Member of VIIRS Science Team  2010-present:  Associate Editor for Journal of Geophysical Research - Atmospheres  2009-2011:  GSFC AeroCenter committee (including chair in 2011)  

											Awards
										
										8/2012: Young Scientist Award from the International Radiation Commission.   1/2011: Best First Authored Paper Award, NASA-GSFC Climate and Radiation Branch  1/2009: Outstanding Scientific Leadership Award, NASA-GSFC Climate and Radiation Branch  2006: Outstanding Performance Award, NASA-GSFC Laboratory for Atmospheres  2005: Outstanding Teamwork Award, NASA-GSFC  7/2002: NCAR's Advanced Study Program, Colloquium on "Aerosols, Climate and the Hydrological Cycle"  12/2002: Outstanding Scientific Support Award, NASA-GSFC Climate and Radiation Branch  

